{"id":"matter-3","label":"States of Matter","pdf":"","lockAfter":3,"list":[{"id":"notes","label":"Notes","type":"passage","data":{"title":"States of Matter","text":"We can see many things around us. Everything we can see and touch is made up of matter. Anything that occupies space and has mass is called matter.\n# What is Mass?\nMass is a measure of how much matter is present in an object. The air we breathe, the food we take, and the water we drink, all have matter in them. \n# What is Volume?\nThe space occupied by an object is called its volume.\n# Three States of Matter\nSolid, liquid and gas are the three states of matter. \nSolid has a fixed shape and fixed volume. eg: pencil, bat, bag, apple, stone, book.\nLiquid does not have a fixed shape. It takes the shape of its container. eg: milk, honey, water, juice, oil, petrol.\nGas does not have a fixed shape and volume. eg: cloud, smoke, gas cylinder (LPG), spray, water vapor, wind."}},{"id":"mcq","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Volume is the ______ occupied by an object.","options":"space, mass, weight, matter"},{"qText":"How many states of matter are there?","options":"three, four, five, two"},{"qText":"Which of the following has volume but does not have shape?","options":"liquid, solid, gas"},{"qText":"Which of the following does not have volume and shape?","options":"gas, liquid, solid"},{"qText":"The amount of matter present in an object is measured by _______.","options":"mass, volume, space, state of matter"}]}},{"id":"classify","label":"Liquid vs Gas","type":"group","data":{"title":"Classify the below as liquid and gas.","types":[{"name":"Liquid","text":"honey, water, juice, oil"},{"name":"Gas","text":"cloud, smoke, LPG, water vapor, wind"}]}},{"id":"true-false","label":"True or False","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"True or False","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Everything we can see is made up of matter.\nGas has no fixed volume.\nA cloud is a form of gas."},{"name":"False","text":"Gas has no mass.\nThe space occupied by an object is called mass."}]}},{"id":"match","label":"Match","type":"match","data":{"title":"Match the related ones.","fontSize":"1rem","text":"space occupied, volume\ntotal matter, mass\nno volume, gas\ndrink, liquid\nfixed shape, solid"}},{"label":"Drag and Drop","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"drag-drop","data":{"text":"*Mass* is a measure of how much matter is in an object.\n*Volume* is the space occupied by an object.\n*Liquid* has no fixed shape but has a fixed volume.\n*Smoke* is a gas.\n*Gas* has no fixed shape and no fixed volume."}},{"id":"notes-2","label":"Change in States of Matter","type":"passage","data":{"title":"Change in States of Matter","text":"Matters change their state as the temperature changes. Solid changes to liquid and liquid changes into gas on heating. Gas becomes liquid and liquid becomes solid on cooling.\n# Melting\nThe change of solid into liquid on heating is called melting. For example, if ice (solid) is heated, it will change into water (liquid).\n# Evaporation\nThe change of a liquid into vapor on heating is called Evaporation. For example, if water is heated, it will change into steam.\n# Freezing\nThe change of liquid into solid on cooling is known as freezing. For example, water (liquid) poured into in ice-tray and placed in the freezer (fridge), gets cooled and becomes ice (solid).\n# Condensation\nThe change of gas into liquid on cooling is called condensation. For example; clouds (gas) on cooling condense and fall as rain (liquid)\n# Experiment\nTake a balance. Keep an air-filled football on one plate and an empty football on another plate. What happens? \nAir filled ball goes down. It is because air has mass."}},{"label":"Drag and Drop","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"drag-drop-2","data":{"text":"*Water* from ocean and rivers *evaporate* and form clouds.\nClouds are in *gas* state. They get cooled by the breeze and fall as *rain*.\nIf we put water in the *freezer*, it becomes *ice*."}},{"id":"mcq-2","label":"Multiple Choice Questions - 2","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Solid becomes ______ on heating.","options":"liquid, gas, water vapor, water"},{"qText":" Change of solid into liquid on heating is called ______.","options":"melting, evaporation, freezing"},{"qText":"Change of gas into liquid on cooling is called ______.","options":"condensation, freezing, evaporation"},{"qText":"Water becomes _____ on heating.","options":"water vapor, cloud, atmosphere"},{"qText":"Change of liquid into solid on cooling is called ______.","options":"freezing, evaporation, melting"}]}},{"id":"true-false-2","label":"True or False","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"True or False","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Change of liquid to gas is called evaporation.\nWhen ice is heated, it becomes water.\nChange of gas into liquid on cooling is called condensation."},{"name":"False","text":"Water is commonly available in gas form.\nMetals like gold and iron cannot be melted."}]}},{"id":"notes-3","label":"Fuel","type":"passage","data":{"title":"Fuel","text":"Paper, firewood, dried leaves and charcoal can be burnt. Liquids like kerosene, petrol and diesel also burn on heating. Domestic gas burns and helps in cooking.\nSubstances when burnt give out heat. But in some substances, the heat released is very low. Thus, these are not used for heating purposes.\nSubstances that give out more heat while burning are used for heating purposes.\nThese substances are called fuels.\nElectrical energy is also used as fuel for cooking and transporting."}},{"id":"mcq-3","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"title":"Multiple Choice Questions","questions":[{"qText":"Gas has ______.","options":"mass, shape, volume"},{"qText":"_____ is used for heating and preparing food.","options":"Fuel,  Paper, Gas"},{"qText":"_______ energy is also used as fuel.","options":"Electrical, Magnetic, Glucose"},{"qText":"______ is the common fuel used in cars.","options":"Petrol, Charcoal, Firewood, LPG"},{"qText":"______ is the common fuel used in cooking.","options":"LPG, Petrol, Paper"},{"qText":"LPG stands for _____.","options":"Liquid Petroleum Gas, Light Petrol Gas, Liquid Petrol Gas"}]}},{"id":"true-false-3","label":"True or False","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"True or False","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Domestic gas (LPG) helps in cooking.\nWater does not catch fire.\nFuels are mainly used for cooking and transportation."},{"name":"False","text":"Electrical energy cannot be used as fuel.\nAll solid matter can be used as a fuel."}]}},{"label":"Drag and Drop","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"drag-drop-3","data":{"text":"Cars run on *petrol*.\n*LPG* is used for cooking.\nThe oven uses *electrical* energy.\nSubstances that give a lot of heat on burning are called *fuel*.\n*Kerosene* is the liquid fuel commonly used for cooking."}},{"id":"match-2","label":"Match","type":"match","data":{"title":"Match the related ones.","fontSize":"1rem","text":"solid to liquid, melting\nwater to vapor, evaporation\nvapor to liquid, condensation\nliquid to solid, freezing"}},{"label":"Drag and Drop","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"drag-drop-4","data":{"text":"Fuel gives *heat* energy on burning.\nAn example of a solid is *stone*.\nAn example of liquid is *water*.\nMoving air in the atmosphere is called *wind*.\nThe measure of matter in an object is called *mass*."}}]}